  <h2><a href="/node/19672" title="slauth ( log in Drupal site using SecondLife / OpenSim credentials )">slauth ( log in Drupal site using SecondLife / OpenSim credentials )</a></h2>

  <div class="meta">
      <span class="submitted">Submitted by <a href="/user/29810" title="View user profile.">ssm2017 Binder</a> on Tue, 2009-03-03 23:01</span>
  
      <div class="terms terms-inline"><a href="/taxonomy/term/86" rel="tag" title="">Drupal</a> · <a href="/taxonomy/term/8088" rel="tag" title="">Linden</a> · <a href="/taxonomy/term/8089" rel="tag" title="">OpenSim</a> · <a href="/taxonomy/term/1604" rel="tag" title="">secondlife</a></div>
    </div>

  <div class="content">
    <div class="vote-up-down-widget">
      <span id="vote_up_19672" class="up-inact" title="You must login to vote!"></span>
    <span id="vote_down_19672" class="down-inact" title="You must login to vote!"></span>
  </div>
<p>hello<br />
here is a new toy/tool to use with SecondLife / OpenSim<br />
<a href="http://drupal.org/project/slauth" title="http://drupal.org/project/slauth">http://drupal.org/project/slauth</a><br />
this is a module to be able to log in a drupal's site using your SecondLife / OpenSim credentials<br />
in the admin panel of the module, you can define the login uri and you can choose a login flow : 0=drupal only / 2=inworld only / 3=drupal -&gt; inworld / 4=inworld -&gt; drupal<br />
to be able to use the drupal login if the inworld login fails or invert...<br />
i hope this will help</p>
  </div>
  
  
